[8] Measles resurgence in the USA
Date: Mon 20 May 2019, accessed July 2019
Source: The Lancet Infectious Diseases [abridged, edited]
https://www.thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(19)30257-9/fulltext


Citation: Sarkar S, Zlojutro A, Khan K, et al.: Measles resurgence in the USA: how international travel compounds vaccine resistance. Lancet Infect Dis. 2019; published online 20 May 2019. doi: https://doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30257-9. Correction to Lancet Infect Dis. 2019; published online 9 May 2019. doi: https://doi.org/10.1016/S1473-3099(19)30231-2.


Hotez and colleagues' recent article highlights the increasing frequency of vaccine-preventable disease cases in Europe and the USA caused by very visible anti-vaccine movements.

The most troubling aspect of this development is the global increase in measles cases. From 1 Jan 2019-26 Apr 2019, the USA reported 704 confirmed measles cases spanning 22 states, compared with 372 reported cases in 2018, 120 in 2017, 86 in 2016, 188 in 2015, and 667 in 2014. Therefore, only 4 months into 2019, the number of cases reported is already the highest since measles was declared officially eliminated in the US in 2000.

[The correction refers to] the list of countries that pose the highest risk of measles to the USA, [which was] corrected to "Ukraine, Mexico, Cuba, Israel, Japan, Thailand, and Philippines."

