[9] Vaccine hesitancy among highly educated
Date: Wed 29 May 2019
Source: The Cut, New York magazine [abridged, edited]
https://www.thecut.com/2019/05/measles-for-the-one-percent.html


...The phenomenon is much more expansive than even that. In the 2017-2018 school year, 7044 kindergartners in Texas had nonmedical exemptions. There were 3344 in Washington state, 3427 in Oregon, 4753 in Michigan, and approximately 2000 in each of New Jersey and New York. But the number of unvaccinated children in the U.S., though small, has risen significantly in the past year. According to the CDC, the percentage of unvaccinated children increased from 0.8% in 2016 to 1.1% in 2017. These 3 tiny decimal points represent a huge increase to about 63 555 unvaccinated kids a year. And vaccination refusal is a contagion, like the measles. People who don't vaccinate their children tend to live among people who also don't vaccinate their children.

[Byline: Lisa Miller]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The article at the source URL above is recommended reading. It helps one understand the philosophy behind the deeply felt vaccine hesitancy of educated parents. It addresses the struggle of such parents with children at Green Meadow Waldorf School, Rockland County, NY, with the court orders to vaccinate their children in response to the growing epidemic of measles in NY. Their view of vaccination with MMR vaccine is that it is introducing toxins into the pure bodies of children. This attitude is partly due to the unfounded fear of autism as well as the consequence of a very active disinformation campaign. The fear of vaccination is prevalent in orthodox religious communities as well as alternative schools such as the Waldorf school. - Mod.LK

