[10] Data requested
Date: Fri 12 Jul 2019
From: Dr. Iype Joseph MBBS, MPH [edited]

It will be interesting if reports with the following data are highlighted:

1. Age data: Those with measles before the age of the 1st dose of measles (e.g., measles cases less than 9 months of age in India. The 1st measles vaccine dose is given at 9 months of age).
2. Age data: Those born before the start of measles vaccination (e.g., those born before 1985 in India).
3. Those [who have] taken vaccinations as recommended by their countries but are still getting measles.

I am part of the measles research group of my institution, RGCB [Rajiv Gandhi Centre for Biotechnology], Trivandrum, Kerala, India. About 27% of our pediatric cases are below 9 months of age. No cases in the above-50-year age group. Some get measles even after getting 2 proper doses of measles vaccine on time. We have few antenatal cases too.

Disaggregated data can help us understand the situation better. The epidemiology of measles is changing. Most of our ideas related to measles developed from what was observed when it was an endemic disease in most parts of the world. The eradication dream may not be as easy as many people have imagined.

--
Dr. Iype Joseph MBBS, MPH
Research scientist (Epidemiology)
Rajiv Gandhi Centre for Biotechnology
Thiruvananthapuram, Kerala,
India. Pin - 695014

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Iype Joseph for his suggestions. Where we can extract this information in reports, we will present it. Such data would be particularly useful in understanding the incidence of measles cases following the full recommended dosage. - Mod.LK]
